  "discussion": "Running in 'llm' mode, ReAct (single attempt) reached exact-match accuracy EM=1.0 while Reflexion (up to several attempts with self-reflection) reached EM=1.0; accuracy did not change by +0.0 absolute. The gain comes at a cost: Reflexion averaged 1.05 attempts versus 1 for ReAct, spending about 61.55 more tokens and -510.1 ms more latency per question on average. The most common ReAct failure modes were no remaining failures, while Reflexion's residual failures were no remaining failures. Reflection memory helped most when the first attempt stopped after the first hop or drifted to a distractor entity, because the reflector could name the missing hop and the actor could complete it next time. It helped least when the answer was simply absent from the provided context, where extra attempts only added cost. The key trade-off is accuracy versus token and latency budget, and evaluator quality bounds the measured gains."
